'''''Technica Curiosa''''' was an early compendium of scientific and medical technologies.  It was published in 1664 by [[Gaspar Schott]]<ref>Schott, Gaspar, ''Technica curiosa, sive mirabilia artis, libris XII comprehensa,'' Nuremberg, Johann Andreas Endter, 1664</ref> near the beginning of the [[scientific revolution]].  It contained some of the first accounts of [[Otto von Guericke]]'s experiments with a vacuum.<ref>https://galileo.ou.edu/exhibits/curious-technology</ref>  One of the first "popular science" publications, the book did much to inspire interest in the sciences.<ref>http://www.technicacuriosa.com </ref>

During 2017, the title 'Technica Curiosa' is being reused for an online publication with content of a similar nature for a modern audience.  It will incorporate the titles of ''[[Popular Astronomy (US magazine)|Popular Astronomy]]'', ''[[Popular Electronics]]'', and ''[[Mechanix Illustrated]]''.{{cn|date=March 2017}}

